ced in the top statistics section, below the header, or within the details panel.\n\n\n**Designing Architecture Graphic**\n\nI'm now deep in designing a dynamic SVG architecture graphic. The goal is to visually represent the Sovereign Enclave Node, the Secure Data Diode, and the GFF Terminal, with real-time feedback. I am working on how the diagram will highlight connections from a specific client enclave, e.g. \"Apex Sovereign Group,\" through the hardware bridge, while showing real-time ping and re-encryption statuses. I'm focusing on making it interactive and custom, with dynamic highlighting on ticket selection.\n\n\n**Visualizing Dynamic Telemetry**\n\nI'm now integrating active telemetry into the graphic. I'm focusing on dynamic displays showing tunnel encryption, bridge integrity, handshake status, and memory isolation. The SVG will feature glowing pathways and display the assigned engineer's name for selected tickets. I'll include an \"Aggregate Oversight State\" when no ticket is selected. I am now reading the code to determine the best location.\n\n\n**Refining Panel Placement**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the best location for the interactive diagnostic visualizer. I'm considering several options: placing it beneath the stats cards and before the filter bar, integrating it into a collapsible panel, or making it a primary, non-collapsible dashboard component. I'm focusing on balancing visibility and space efficiency, thinking about how it should interact with the ticket selection and filtering processes. I'm exploring different layouts to determine the most intuitive and elegant integration. The overall layout consists of a header, stats, filter bar, and a table.\n\n\n**Optimizing Screen Real Estate**\n\nI'm now contemplating layout adjustments, particularly for large screens. A two-column structure is being considered, where the search, filter, and table reside on the left, while the interactive \"Secure Bridge Diagnostic Console\" occupies the right. I'm focusing on the current fixed slide-out drawer implementation, and am thinking of positioning the diagram directly within this drawer, perhaps under the \"Diagnostic\" or \"Assets\" tab, or as a visual header. This should ensure responsiveness and contextual relevance.\n\n\n**Positioning the Visualizer**\n\nI am now focusing on placement within the existing diagnostic drawer. I'm imagining a collapsible block at the top of the \"Diagnostic\" tab for the visualizer. I am considering integrating it into the existing `diagnostic` tab. The `selectedTicket` has a description; I may use this to provide context. The tab currently displays details like created date and SLA seconds. I am reviewing the code to ensure it fits the existing structure.\n\n\n**Integrating Visual Diagnostics**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the tactical console concept, aiming for an immersive cyber-defense feel. The SVG will animate telemetry flowing from the Enclave VM, through the Attestation Engine, to the GFF gateway. The bridge state will dynamically update based on ticket status. Key variables like SLA count and security clearance will be displayed. I am now implementing code to support the visual design, and confirm real-time data flow.\n\n\n**Enhancing Modal Visuals**\n\nI'm now focusing on the \"Add Ticket\" modal. It feels a bit generic compared to the diagnostic console. I plan to enhance its premium feel. Specifically, I'll evaluate the aesthetics of the \"Add Ticket\" modal, ensuring it aligns with our high-end 2026 AI site. I'll consider styling the \"Add Ticket\" modal with the dark theme and neon highlights to match other premium UI elements. I need to make the modal \"pop\" to be premium!\n\n\n**Refining Modal Aesthetics**\n\nI'm now iterating on the \"Add Ticket\" modal design. While the current modal has a good base, it needs enhancements. I'm focusing on styling, highlighting inputs, and modern borders, ensuring the premium feel. I'll make the modal fit our 2026 AI site aesthetic. I'm also planning to review the stats cards as part of this process.\n\n\n**Implementing Ticket Interactions**\n\nI'm now focusing on adding micro-interactions to the ticket rows. I envision subtle background highlights, glows, and custom tooltips on hover. I'm exploring sliding indicators, glowing badges, and quick actions to enhance the user experience. I will also incorporate accessibility focus rings for each row.\n\n\n**Enhancing Accessibility Integration**\n\nI'm now integrating keyboard accessibility for ticket rows. I am adding `tabIndex`, `onKeyDown`, and a `role` attribute to the `<tr>` elements to ensure keyboard-only users can interact. I'm focusing on handling `Enter` and `Space` key presses to select a ticket. The objective is to make all UI elements keyboard-navigable and interactive, improving the overall user experience.\n\n\n**Improving Ticket Accessibility**\n\nI've successfully implemented keyboard accessibility for ticket rows, adding `tabIndex`, `onKeyDown`, and `role` attributes, to streamline selection. I also did the same for the mobile view. The focus is now on ensuring keyboard users can easily interact. I've also incorporated `Enter` and `Space` key handling for keyboard compatibility.\n\n\n**Designing Diagnostic Component**\n\nI'm now detailing the \"Sovereign Enclave Diagnostics Bridge\" visual. It will render at the top of the selected ticket drawer, directly under the header. This section will feature an SVG/CSS graphic for an immersive cyber-defense aesthetic, dynamic real-time telemetry, and key performance indicators. The goal is to provide a rich visual experience with quick insights into the status of the enclave.\n\n\n**Visualizing Interactive Bridge**\n\nI'm now detailing the interactive SVG for the GFF Isolation Bridge. I'm focusing on dynamic visualizations:  a pulsing indicator for the client enclave, a dashed path with flow animations representing data tunnels, and status-based path color changes to provide immediate insights into ticket status.  My focus is on a clear and immersive representation.\n\n\n**Crafting Diagnostic Visuals**\n\nI'm now implementing the SVG graphic for the \"GFF Admin Terminal\". The graphic is designed to be interactive with flashing lights. I'll include the assigned engineer's name, or \"UNASSIGNED\" in blinking red if there isn't one. Beneath, I'll add an enclave indicator, telemetry, and an SLA countdown timer, and create the corresponding CSS animations directly within the component for a self-contained and clean implementation.\n\n\n**Implementing SVG Animations**\n\nI'm now integrating the SVG animation into the diagnostic component. I've defined animation keyframes for flow effects and applied them with CSS classes for speed control. I'm focusing on responsiveness, utilizing a `viewBox` for dynamic sizing, and am now working on the path animations. I'm choosing a Bezier curve to connect the nodes for a premium feel.\n\n\\n\\nI'm now implementing the SVG animations, including a flow animation for a Bezier curve path, with varying speeds to indicate different states. The goal is to provide a visually engaging, high-performance display of data flow between the client enclave and the GFF admin console. I've configured the animations to be seamless and dynamically reflect the ticket status.\n\n\n**Animating Diagnostic Flows**\n\nI am now implementing the specified SVG animations. I'm focusing on the glowing overlays for data flow, dynamically updating stroke colors and speeds based on ticket status: red for open, cyan for investigating, and amber for hold. A small, glowing hardware-diode badge will display tunnel status, with a pulse ring around the active node. My goal is dynamic and clear visualizations.\n\n\n**Refining Animation Integration**\n\nI'm now integrating the SVG animation into the diagnostics component, focusing on responsive size and styling with CSS. I am adjusting speed, colors, and flow effects to provide a clear depiction of ticket state